{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"985c5c98-e725-49b6-b5b6-e0f8655ef788","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n### 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at the solution root, for consistency)\n\nAdd or merge these properties into your `Directory.Build.props`:\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `EnableMSTestRunner` | Switches from VSTest to the Microsoft.Testing.Platform-based MSTest runner |\n| `OutputType` → `Exe` | Each test project becomes a self-contained executable (required by the new runner) |\n| `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` | Lets `dotnet test` drive the new platform instead of VSTest |\n\n### 2. Each test `.csproj` — add the TRX package\n\nThe old VSTest `--logger trx` flag won't work. TRX reporting is now an opt-in extension:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n```\n\n### 3. CI command change\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nArguments after `--` are forwarded to the testing platform. TRX files are written to each project's `TestResults/` folder by default.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of per-project changes:** only the new `PackageReference`. Everything else is handled centrally by `Directory.Build.props`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"443e7ed2-a871-4404-9e15-65841bed6d92","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **In each test project's `.csproj`** (or better, in a `Directory.Build.props` for consistency):\n   - Add `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` to enable `dotnet test` integration with the new platform\n   - Add `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` to use the MSTest runner (which is the Microsoft.Testing.Platform-based runner for MSTest)\n   - Set `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` since test projects become self-contained executables\n\n2. **For TRX reporting**: MSTest 3.8.0 integrates Microsoft.Testing.Platform directly, so TRX support comes built-in through the platform's extensions rather than requiring a separate logger package.\n\nWith MSTest 3.x, the key configuration is enabling the platform runner via `EnableMSTestRunner`, setting the output type to executable, and ensuring `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is true for `dotnet test` compatibility. For TRX reports, I can either add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package and use the `--report-trx` flag, or rely on the platform's dotnet test integration to handle the standard `--logger trx` flag. So `--logger trx` is a VSTest concept that won't work with the new platform—instead I need `--report-trx`. With `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` enabled, I can pass arguments to the testing platform using `dotnet test -- --report-trx`, or run the test executable directly. For consistency across projects, I should configure this in Directory.Build.props by setting the necessary properties like `EnableMSTestRunner` and `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`. I'm realizing the exact command syntax depends on the SDK version—with .NET 8.0.400 and newer, `dotnet test --report-trx` works directly, but older versions need the `--` separator. The safest approach is using `Directory.Build.props` to centralize these settings across all test projects.","outputTokens":1787,"requestId":"67CC:26153C:29ACD4A:2DEF9D4:69FD3379"},"id":"f1256878-67ba-48d4-ac0d-ea4564322971","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:51:41.373Z","parentId":"c6fd3334-dc9b-4296-b447-eb0d99cfdfea"}
